definition.value: The anion of 2-oxononanoic acid.
A butyric acid derivative having an oxo group at the 2-position and a hydroxymethylphosphinyl moiety at the 4-position.
The carboxylate anion of 4-(hydroxymethylphosphinyl)-2-oxobutyric acid.
A propanoic acid derivative having an (R)-hydroxy substituent at the 2-position and a 1H-indol-3-yl group at the 3-position.
The conjugate base of (R)-indole-3-lactic acid.
A propanoic acid derivative having an (R)-hydroxy substituent at the 2-position and a 5-benzyloxy-1H-indol-3-yl group at the 3-position.
The conjugate base of (R)-3-(5-benzyloxyindol-3-yl)lactic acid.
A propanoic acid derivative having an (R)-hydroxy substituent at the 2-position and a fluoro substituent at the 3-position.
The conjugate base of (S)-3-fluorolactic acid.
The (R)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid. Found in patients with short-bowel syndrome (an inborn error of metabolism), and in maple syrup urine disease, MSUD.
The anion of (R)-2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid.

A valeric acid derivative having an (R)-hydroxy substituent at the 2-position and an (S)-methyl substituent at the 3-position; one of 4 steroisomers of 2-hydroxy-3-methylpentanoic acid, generated by isoleucine metabolism. Found at significantly higher levels than normal in patients with maple syrup urine disease (MSUD).
The conjugate base of (2R,3S)-2-hydroxy-3-methylpentanoic acid.
A nine-carbon straight-chain (2R)-2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid.
The hydrochloride salt of glycinexylidide.
The anion of (R)-2-hydroxynonanoic acid.
An adipic acid derivative having a (2R)-hydroxy substituent.
Amino acid amide with 2,6-dimethylanilino and 2-aminobutanoyl components.
The conjugate base of (R)-2-hydroxyadipic acid.
A butyric acid derivative having an (R)-hydroxy sbustituent at the 2-position and a hydroxymethylphosphinyl moiety at the 4-position.
A substituted aniline in which the aniline ring carries 4-hydroxy and 2,6-dimethyl substituents; a urinary metabolite of lidocaine.
A substituted aniline in which the aniline ring carries 4-hydroxy and 6-methyl substituents; a urinary metabolite of lidocaine.
The conjugate base of (R)-2-hydroxy-4-(hydroxymethylphosphinyl)butyric acid
A sulfonamide antibiotic in which 4-aminobenzenesulfonic acid and 4,5-dimethyl-1,3-oxazol-2-amine have combined to form the sulfonamide bond.
An methoxyisoflavone having methoxy substituents at the 6- and 2'-positions, a hydroxy group at position 7 and a methylenedioxy moiety at the 4'- and 5'-positions.

A spiroketal resulting from the formal condensation of the keto group of cyclohexanone with the hydroxy groups of 1-(2,3-dihydroxypropyl)guanidine. A postganglionic adrenergic blocking agent formerly used (generally as the sulfate salt) for the management of hypertension, it has been largely superseded by other drugs less likely to cause orthostatic hypotension (dizzy spells on standing up or stretching).
A 7-[beta-D-apiofuranosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-glucopyranosyloxy]isoflavone having four methoxy substituents at the 2'-, 4'-, 5'- and 6-positions.
A member of the class of 7-hydroxyisoflavones that is isoflavone having four methoxy substituents at the 2'-, 4'-, 5'- and 6-positions and a hydroxy group at position 7.
A pyrimidine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 3'-monophosphate having thymine as the nucleobase.
A deoxyguanosine phosphate having a monophosphate group located at the 3'-position.
An inosine phosphate having a monophosphate group located at the 3'-position.
An N-acyl-L-homoserine lactone having dodecanoyl as the acyl substituent.

An organic sulfate salt resulting from the reaction of 2 eq. guanadrel with 1 eq. sulfuric acid. A postganglionic adrenergic blocking agent formerly used for the management of hypertension, it has been largely superseded by other drugs less likely to cause orthostatic hypotension (dizzy spells on standing up or stretching).
A member of the class of  guanidines in which one of the hydrogens of the amino group has been replaced by a 2-azocan-1-ylethyl group.
An antifungal macrolactone antibiotic, obtained from Diheterospora chlamydosporia and Chaetomium chiversii that inhibits protein tyrosine kinase and heat shock protein 90 (Hsp90).
An aryl sulfide having two 5-chloro-2-hydroxyphenyl groups attached to sulfur; an antiinfective drug mostly used in veterinary medicine.

An aromatic ether resulting from oxidative dimerisation between the 4-hydroxy group of one molecule of (1R)-1-(4-hydroxybenzyl)-6-methoxy-2-methyl-1,2,3,4-tetrahydroisoquinolin-7-ol and the 3-position of the 4-hydroxybenzyl group of another.

A member of the class of guanidines that is dioctylamine in which a hydrogen from each of the terminal methyl groups is replaced by a guanidino group. Once used as a fungicidal seed dressing, it is no longer approved for use in the European Union.
A alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is nicotinic acid which has been hydrogenated at the 1-2 and 5-6 positions of the pyridine ring.
A sapogenin that is olean-12-en-28-oic acid substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3 and an oxo group at position 23.
